AUDIO: 'lab, which even beats the top closed models. OpenAI releases their latest model, GPT 5.1. This might be the first ever official marriage between a human and an AI chatbot. This AI allows you to'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'drag stuff around and turn that into a seamless video. We have a freaking humanoid robot army and a lot more. So, let\'s jump right in. First up, researchers at Google DeepMind made a'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'breakthrough in teaching AI systems to see the world more like humans do. This is of course important for building more intuitive and trustworthy AI systems. So, here\'s the article. It\'s just titled'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Teaching AI to see the world more like we do. And you see, here\'s the problem. Current AI vision models don\'t always see the world as humans do. Sure, they can identify objects, but they don\'t'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'always understand the relationships between them. For example, an AI system might fail to recognize that a car and an airplane are both large vehicles made of metal, or for example, that a giraffe and a cat are both mammals and are very'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different from a tennis ball. Now, to understand the differences between human and AI vision, researchers used this classic odd oneout task from cognitive science. This is a task where you are'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'given three images and asked to determine which one does not fit with the others. In other words, which one is the odd one out? And this test actually revealed some surprising differences between how AI models and how humans'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interpret things. So, for example, if you look at this first row here, by the way, what the hell is this? No, I\'m just kidding. I know this is a tape, which are super cute, by the way, especially'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the babies. Here are like more baby tapers for your reference. But anyways, if you look at this first row here, you can see that both the AI model and the human were able to identify the correct'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'odd one out, which is this birthday cake because it\'s not an animal. So here, both the AI model and the human are aligned. However, if you look at this row at the bottom, naturally the human'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'would choose this sea star as the odd one out because it\'s not a mammal. But interestingly, the AI model actually chose this cat instead of the sea star. So, here\'s an example where it\'s not'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really aligned with human perception. So, how do we train or fine-tune an AI model to be more aligned? Well, the researchers proposed a three-step method. First, they trained a teacher model by basically training this small'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'adapter on top of a powerful pre-trained vision model. and they trained it on this things data set which contains millions of examples of odd oneout questions with human answers. Now after'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'training this teacher model for the second step they actually used this teacher model to generate a massive new data set of millions of humanlike odd oneout decisions and they called this'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data set alignet and finally they used this synthetic data set to basically train or fine-tune a smaller student AI model so that it can be more aligned with human perception. And so you can'

[03:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see from this chart here after training the model with alignet the student model in blue showed way higher human alignment across a range of visual tasks. So you can see the accuracy is a'

